## When you *do* want to map a colour to data

::: panel-tabset
### plot

![](index_files/figure-revealjs/bill-species-1.png){width="80%"}

### code


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = bill_length_mm,
           y = bill_depth_mm,
           group = species)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = species, 
                 shape = species),
             size = 3,
             alpha = 0.8)
```
:::


Note that `color` and `shape` are *inside* `aes()` but `size` and `alpha` are *outside*.
:::

## Add additional geoms

::: panel-tabset
### plot

![]( index_files/figure-revealjs/bill-species-smooth-1.png){width="80%"}

### code


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = bill_length_mm,
           y = bill_depth_mm,
           group = species)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = species, 
                 shape = species),
             size = 3,
             alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", aes(color = species))
```
:::

:::

## Scales in ggplot2

> Scales in ggplot2 control the mapping from data to aesthetics. They take your data and turn it into something that you can see, like size, colour, position or shape. They also provide the tools that let you interpret the plot: the axes and legends.

Three groups of scales:

-   position scales and axes
-   colour scales and legends
-   scales for other aesthetics

## Add a colour scale

::: panel-tabset
### plot

![]( index_files/figure-revealjs/bill-species-colour-1.png){width="80%"}

### code


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = bill_length_mm,
           y = bill_depth_mm,
           group = species)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = species, 
                 shape = species),
             size = 3,
             alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", aes(color = species)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("darkorange","purple","cyan4"))
```
:::

:::

## Facets

::: panel-tabset
### plot 1

![]( index_files/figure-revealjs/bill-species-facet-1.png){width="80%"}

### code 1


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = bill_length_mm,
           y = bill_depth_mm,
           group = species)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = species, 
                 shape = species),
             size = 3,
             alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", aes(color = species)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("darkorange","purple","cyan4")) +
  facet_wrap(~species)
```
:::


### plot 2

![]( index_files/figure-revealjs/bill-species-facet-free-x-1.png){width="80%"}

### code 2


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = bill_length_mm,
           y = bill_depth_mm,
           group = species)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = species, 
                 shape = species),
             size = 3,
             alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", aes(color = species)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("darkorange","purple","cyan4")) +
  facet_wrap(~species, scales = "free_x")
```
:::

:::

## First example: add theme elements

::: panel-tabset
### plot

![]( index_files/figure-revealjs/bill-species-theme-1.png){width="80%"}

### code


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(data = penguins,
       aes(x = bill_length_mm,
           y = bill_depth_mm,
           group = species)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = species, 
                 shape = species),
             size = 3,
             alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", aes(color = species)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("darkorange","purple","cyan4")) +
  labs(title = "Penguin bill dimensions",
       x = "bill length (mm)",
       y = "bill depth (mm)") +
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(plot.title.position = "plot",
        text = element_text(size = 20))
```
:::

:::

